data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern identified: **Timeout enforcement**

The code spawns a thread, waits with `Join(timeout)`, and calls `Thread.Abort()` if it exceeds the deadline. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it simply doesn't work.

### The fundamental shift

**.NET Framework** — preemptive: the runtime forcibly injects `ThreadAbortException` into the thread.
**.NET 8** — cooperative: the work must voluntarily check for cancellation. Nothing can force-kill a managed thread.

---

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout. Task.WaitAsync throws
            // OperationCanceledException when the token fires.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If your work can cooperate (preferred)

Add a `CancellationToken`-accepting overload so the work itself can bail out early:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Usage — the work checks the token at regular intervals:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | The first overload (no token) detaches from the result but the `Task.Run` delegate keeps running in the background. This is the biggest behavioral difference from `Thread.Abort`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch your own timeout, not an unrelated cancellation. |
| **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** | It holds an internal timer. Leaking it leaks the timer. Always `using`. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort` has no equivalent** | The old catch that called `ResetAbort()` to keep the thread alive is gone. With cooperative cancellation, you check `token.IsCancellationRequested` and decide whether to continue — no exception is injected in the first place. |
| **Blocking calls won't respond to the token** | If `work()` calls `Thread.Sleep(60000)` or a blocking socket read, it won't wake up on cancellation. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O. |

### What was removed and why

| .NET Framework API | Replacement | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` / `CancelAfter` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` | API doesn't exist; cooperative model doesn't need it |
| Manual `Thread` + `Join` | `Task.Run` + `WaitAsync` | Cleaner, composable, supports cancellation natively |

**Bottom line:** If you control the work delegate, always pass and check the `CancellationToken` — that's the only way to guarantee the work actually stops promptly.
